---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'plan';
const description =
  'Author a Plan Mode contract before any non-trivial change. Names files, approach, verification, rollback. The human stays the architect. The agent is the implementer.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="commands" eyebrow="Command">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    A short, structured plan written <em>before</em> any code. Reviewed and
    approved as a contract. Code that strays from the plan is rejected. If
    reality forces a change, the plan is updated first. Not bureaucracy.
    Cognitive debt prevention.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this command exists</h2>
  <p>
    The fastest way to accumulate cognitive debt is to let an agent run for an
    hour, accept a 600-line diff, and ship it. The code works. The tests pass.
    Six weeks later someone needs to change it and nobody knows why it works.
    Knowledge erosion. Cognitive surrender.
  </p>
  <p>
    Plan Mode is the cheap insurance against that. Before any non-trivial
    change, the agent (or the human) writes a plan: <em>intent</em>,
    <em>files touched</em>, <em>approach</em>, <em>verification</em>,
    <em>out of scope</em>, <em>rollback</em>. The human reviews it as a
    contract. Only then does code get written.
  </p>
  <p>
    The point is not the document. The point is the act of writing it. It
    forces the agent to map the change before doing it, surfaces the
    files-touched count before they are touched, and makes scope creep
    visible. Out-of-scope is at least two bullets, always. The agent's instinct
    is to expand scope; that section is the leash.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Read first" tone="ember">
    <p>
      Plan Mode is one of the four
      <a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>cognitive debt repayment
      practices</a> and a standard
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>good practice</a>. The
      <a href={url('blueprint/#cognitive-debt')}>2026 Blueprint</a> names it as
      mandatory in high-performing teams.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>When to reach for it</h2>
  <p>
    Required for any change touching more than three files, or refactors, or
    migrations, or anything affecting a public API. The exact threshold lives
    in your <code>.context/conventions.md</code>, set by
    <a href={url('commands/init/')}><code>init</code></a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Optional but recommended for smaller changes. A two-file change can still
    benefit from a five-line plan, and the discipline pays for itself.
  </p>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <p>One file:</p>
  <pre><code>.context/plans/&lt;YYYY-MM-DD&gt;-&lt;slug&gt;.md</code></pre>
  <p>
    The structure is non-negotiable. Sections: <strong>Intent</strong> (the
    why), <strong>Files touched</strong> (a real list, not aspirational),
    <strong>Approach</strong> (two or three sentences),
    <strong>Verification</strong> (real commands),
    <strong>Out of scope</strong> (at least two bullets),
    <strong>Rollback</strong>, <strong>Risks</strong>, <strong>Notes</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The plan file survives after the change ships. Status moves from
    <em>draft</em> → <em>approved</em> → <em>in-progress</em> →
    <em>shipped</em>. It becomes context for future agents: <em>we did this;
    here is why</em>.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Understand the task.</strong> If it is vague, ask one focused
      question. The "Intent" paragraph has to be fillable confidently.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Read the relevant code.</strong> Map the files that will be
      touched. The list must be accurate, not aspirational.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Draft.</strong> Fill each section. Approach is two or three
      sentences, not a design doc.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Show the plan, wait for approval.</strong> Three options:
      approve, edit, reject. Do not start coding before approval. This is the
      entire point.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Make the checkpoint commit.</strong> Record the hash in the
      plan. If anything goes sideways during implementation, you have a
      known-good state.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Implement, verifying as you go.</strong> Run the verification
      commands after each meaningful step. If the implementation reveals the
      plan was wrong: stop, update the plan, re-show, continue once
      re-approved.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Mark shipped.</strong> Update status, record the merge commit.
      Leave the file in the repo.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Prompt for ADRs.</strong> If the plan made a technology choice,
      explicitly rejected an alternative, or introduced a new convention,
      offer to draft an <a href={url('commands/adr/')}><code>adr</code></a>.
      Never write ADRs without asking.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="The quality bar" tone="mute">
    <p>
      Out-of-scope has at least two bullets and they are specific. The "why"
      is real: not "to improve the code" but the specific reason the change
      is happening <em>now</em>. The verification commands actually run.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Failure modes the command guards against</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Plan written after the fact.</strong> That is a retro. Useful,
      but not what this command does.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Plan that is a design doc.</strong> Approach is two or three
      sentences. If it is a page, you are writing the wrong artifact.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>No out-of-scope.</strong> The agent will scope-creep. Always.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>No checkpoint commit.</strong> When the change goes sideways
      (it sometimes will), you have nothing to revert to.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related ideas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>Cognitive debt</a>. Plan
      Mode is the third repayment practice.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/good-practices/')}>Good practices</a>. Plan
      Mode discipline, defensive commits, interface-first development.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('commands/adr/')}><code>adr</code></a>. The natural
      follow-up when a plan made a durable decision.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#cognitive-debt')}>2026 Blueprint: Plan Mode</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CommandPager slug="plan" />
</Doc>
